x4freetext: Alice ORSAY accelerator
Natural elemental sample (1 to 1.5 mg/cm2 thick)
evaporated onto an Al-foil.
Additional Al foils served As catchers and were counted
together with the target foils.
Depending on the incident beam and energy,
a single target or stacked targets were chosen.
The incident energy was varied either by changing the
acceleration parameters, or by using Al degraders.
In the latter case, the energy reduction was
calculated by means of the range-energy table of
L.C.Northcliffe (1970).

x4freetext: range-energy table
The range-energy values of NORTHCLIFFE contain
systematic errors (R.Bimbot et al., nucl.Instr.Meth.
153(1978)161). It is unknown whether or not
corrections for these errors were applied here.
Including
- errors of the energy of the incident beam,
- uncertainties on energy losses in Al degraders.
This last error was estimated to be 15% of the energy
loss.
The uncertainties on cross sections include,
beam flux measurement              (2%),
target thickness and homogeneity   (5%),
counting efficiencies for alpha,
counting efficiencies for gamma    (4%),
branching ratios for gamma emitters,
statistical errors of activities.

The purity of the Ca-40 beam was tested in a
subsequent experiment by irradiating a thick Al-foil.
In case of a contamination with Ar-40 ions an activity
of Ar-41 could Be measured. The cross section for the
production of this NUCLIDE being very small with Ca-40
projectiles, and much larger with Ar-40 ions. The
method is sensitive to a 1% Ar-40 contamination
The incident energy of the projectiles was
determined by the scattered proton technique, thus
lowering the energy error to about 0.5%.
The value of 0.0015 given in the paper is probably
a misprint + see flag(3.)
